1. Normalised Extract: Core Implementation Details

Function purpose and return
- fizzBuzz(n): Given a positive integer n, produce an ordered sequence for i = 1..n where:
  - if i % 3 === 0 and i % 5 === 0, value is "FizzBuzz"
  - else if i % 3 === 0, value is "Fizz"
  - else if i % 5 === 0, value is "Buzz"
  - else value is the decimal string representation of i
- The function returns an array of strings of length n, where each element corresponds to the transformed value for that index.

Input validation (explicit, exact checks to implement)
- If typeof n !== 'number' then throw a TypeError with message: n must be a number
- If Number.isInteger(n) === false then throw a TypeError with message: n must be an integer
- If n <= 0 then throw a RangeError with message: n must be > 0

Algorithm (imperative implementation)
- Create an array result = [] with capacity n (pre-allocate length where supported)
- For i from 1 to n inclusive:
  - if (i % 15 === 0) push 'FizzBuzz'
  - else if (i % 3 === 0) push 'Fizz'
  - else if (i % 5 === 0) push 'Buzz'
  - else push String(i)
- Return result

Performance characteristics
- Time complexity: O(n) single pass
- Space complexity: O(n) for the returned array (optionally O(1) if streaming output instead of returning)

ESM export and module packaging (exact lines to use)
- Named export (preferred for testable library functions):
  export function fizzBuzz(n) { /* implementation */ }
- Default export variant (alternative):
  export default function fizzBuzz(n) { /* implementation */ }
- Node.js (file extension and package.json): ensure package.json contains "type": "module" to allow .js ESM imports in Node >= 12+; otherwise use .mjs extension for module files.

2. Supplementary Details: Specs and Implementation Notes

Type and error semantics
- TypeError thrown for wrong JS type or non-integer values. Use checks in this order: typeof check, then Number.isInteger.
- RangeError thrown for out-of-range numeric values (n <= 0). Use explicit message to aid tests.

Alternate return shapes
- Default recommended: return string[] where numbers are stringified to maintain uniform array element type.
- Alternative: return Array<string|number> to preserve numeric values for non-Fizz/Buzz entries; this complicates downstream formatting and tests—avoid unless required.

Streaming/output variants
- For very large n, provide an alternative API: fizzBuzzStream(n, onValue) where onValue(value: string, index: number) is invoked for each produced value; this reduces memory from O(n) to O(1).
- Implement streaming variant by iterating and invoking callback, returning undefined when complete.

Edge-case handling
- n === 1 should return ['1']
- n === 3 should return ['1','2','Fizz']
- n === 5 should return ['1','2','Fizz','4','Buzz']
- Validate for NaN: treat as TypeError (typeof NaN === 'number' but Number.isInteger(NaN) === false)

